  "unmapped_findings": [
    "2.5 wt.% Al alloying increased the austenite lattice parameter by 1.41 × 10^-3 nm relative to the base alloy, while 2.5 wt.% Si had a minimal effect. Linear lattice parameter coefficients A^LP found: Si = -0.018 × 10^-3 nm wt.%^-1, Al = 0.582 × 10^-3 nm wt.%^-1, consistent with Dyson and Holmes [16].",
    "SFE results: Base alloy 26.3 ± 3.0 mJ m^-2; 2.5 Si alloy 19.9 ± 2.0 mJ m^-2; 2.5 Al alloy 38.3 ± 6.1 mJ m^-2. Linear SFE coefficients A^SFE found: Si = -2.6 mJ m^-2 wt.%^-1, Al = 4.9 mJ m^-2 wt.%^-1, in good agreement with thermochemical modeling for Al (~5.2 mJ m^-2 wt.%^-1) and high-Mn literature for Si (-1 to -3.5 mJ m^-2 wt.%^-1).",
    "Ignoring Al effect on lattice parameter overestimates retained austenite C content by δ_C = x_Al (A_Al^LP / A_C^LP); for 1 wt.% Al, δ_C is estimated at 0.125–0.176 wt.%, which is non-negligible relative to the carbon levels that influence austenite thermodynamic stability.",
    "Williams and Carter [34] correction for partial dislocation strain fields was estimated but not applied to primary SFE data due to incomplete TEM parameters. Upper limit estimation suggests corrected SFE for 2.5 Al alloy would be 44.0 ± 9.8 mJ m^-2, while other alloys change by ~1 mJ m^-2 or less.",
    "Figure 1 shows a WBDF TEM micrograph of a dissociated dislocation in the base alloy, with annotations of d (partial separation) and α (character angle), and a scale bar of 50 nm, illustrating the g//b imaging condition.",
    "Figure 2 scatter plot and Table 2 caption data show the dependence of austenite lattice parameter on relative Si and Al alloying (wt pct).",
    "Figure 3(a) scatter plot presents measured partial dislocation separation vs. perfect dislocation character angle for all three alloys, with solid lines indicating average SFE and dashed lines showing standard deviation bounds. Figure 3(b) scatter plot shows dependence of SFE on relative Si and Al alloying (wt pct).",
    "The paper's findings are limited to fully austenitic Fe-Ni-Cr steels; extension to multiphase low-alloy AHSS assumes Si and Al effects are independent of Ni and Cr alloying, and that no element partitioning occurs in the single-phase structure."
